{"lc": 1, "type": "constructor", "id": ["langchain", "schema", "document", "Document"], "kwargs": {"metadata": {"producer": "Adobe PDF Library 17.0", "creator": "Adobe InDesign 19.5 (Macintosh)", "creationdate": "2025-06-30T13:23:51+01:00", "moddate": "2025-06-30T13:23:54+01:00", "trapped": "/False", "source": "corpus\\autistic-spectrum-v4.pdf", "total_pages": 47, "page": 33, "page_label": "34"}, "page_content": "to them.\nwww.autism.org.uk/advice-and-guidance/topics/resources-for-autistic-teenagers\nExplaining autism to relatives and friends\nIt can be hard for relatives and friends to understand autism as they may have no \nexperience of it. It\u2019s important to remember that parents have a lot longer to get their \nheads around their autistic child than other people in their lives. Parents may believe \nthere is something different about their child from a very early age and may learn \nabout autism before their child receives a diagnosis. \nThe link below includes some tips on explaining autism to grandparents (or other \npeople who help look after your child) but bear in mind that it may be quite a lot for \nthem to take on all at once.\nwww.bristolautismsupport.org/grandparents-dont-believe-child-autistic", "type": "Document"}}